Pressure builds on Davis to relax air standards =20



Updated: May 24, 2001 - 2:22 p.m. =20

A major electricity supplier said Thursday it will sharply cut prices=20
for power from three Southern California plants in anticipation that=20
air quality monitors will let the plants release more pollution this=20
summer. =20

Meanwhile, aides said Gov. Gray Davis will consider paying=20
businesses to run heavily polluting diesel generators to boost the=20
state's power supply and help avert rolling blackouts. =20

Reliant Energy said it could chop its power bids from the high of=20
$1,900 per megawatt hour Davis criticized this month to as little as=20
$150 per megawatt hour -- but only if air regulators quickly allow it=20
to exceed pollution standards at the three plants. =20

The Houston-based generator will cut its prices immediately, but=20
will soon be forced to shut down three of its five Southern California=20
plants for the rest of the year if pollution standards aren't lifted, said=20
Joe Bob Perkins, president and CEO of Reliant Energy Wholesale=20
Group. =20

Davis singled out Reliant's $1,900-per-megawatt-hour charge earlier=20
this month as an example of the egregious prices he said=20
generators should voluntarily cut. =20

Reliant said it deliberately bid the high price to discourage the=20
state's power grid operator from calling its high-polluting plants into=20
use. Using the plants now eats up valuable pollution credits that=20
will likely be needed to keep the plants running during even higher=20
demand periods this summer, the company said. =20

"In essence, we are doing exactly what Gov. Gray Davis has=20
suggested. But if these restrictions are not lowered, we will run out=20
of power from these units very quickly," Perkins said in a=20
statement. =20

Perkins proposed that emissions hours not be counted against=20
Reliant's yearly allotment whenever the plants are called into=20
operation to help prevent blackouts. =20

Reliant's Mandalay, Etiwanda and Ellwood plants each face annual=20
air pollution limits imposed by the South Coast Air Quality=20
Management District and the Santa Barbara County and Ventura=20
County air pollution control districts. Reliant has asked for=20
extensions from each of the districts. =20

"There's no question we are in an emergency situation. We will=20
consider every option available" to avert blackouts, said Davis=20
spokesman Roger Salazar. But he said the administration had not=20
seen Reliant's proposal. =20

Davis also will consider paying businesses to fire up their backup=20
generators when necessary to avoid outages, Salazar said.=20
Running the generators would let the businesses disconnect from=20
the state's power grid, freeing up electricity for other uses. =20

The proposals have consumer and environmental groups outraged. =20

"It's a short-term fix that will have potential long-term health=20
consequences," said Paul Knepprath of the American Lung=20
Association of California. =20

The state should instead cut demand by encouraging more=20
conservation, the lung association and 18 other consumer and=20
environmental groups said in a letter to Davis on Wednesday. =20

Davis already is promoting conservation, but blackouts have health=20
and public safety consequences too, Salazar said. The use of=20
backup generators is being proposed by the administration's top=20
energy advisers, but Davis has not yet seen the proposal, Salazar=20
said. =20

The governor is willing to "explore every conceivable option for=20
generation this summer," Salazar said. =20

The twin developments come the same week the administration cut=20
by 20 percent its estimate of new power generation that will be=20
available this summer. Davis now projects 4,000 additional=20
megawatts, 1,000 megawatts short of his original estimate. A=20
megawatt is enough power for about 750 homes.=20
